{"timestamp": "2026-03-01T01:56:05.975832+00:00", "run_id": "2a3ff9f7-ef9f-46de-934c-49ff50efd604", "event_type": "ENV_EVENT_LOGGED", "payload": {"env_id": "2a3ff9f7-ef9f-46de-934c-49ff50efd604", "actor_id": "human", "event_type": "ARTIFACT_INGESTED", "payload": {"artifact": {"artifact_id": "76810f23-e1c1-4698-b845-8a1fededfa9e", "artifact_type": "product_idea", "title": "Supermemory", "content": "Supermemory.ai is a high\u2011throughput, low\u2011latency memory infrastructure layer that sits between AI clients and foundation models to provide persistent, semantically indexed, multi\u2011modal context at scale, exposed via a universal Memory API and transparent HTTP router. [supermemory](https://supermemory.ai)\n\n## Core role and architecture\n\nSupermemory implements \u201ccontext engineering infrastructure\u201d that externalizes long\u2011term and cross\u2011session state from the LLM into a dedicated memory engine.  It provides a Postgres\u2011backed transactional store coupled with a custom vector search engine deployed on Cloudflare Durable Objects, allowing per\u2011user memory footprints up to roughly 50M tokens and an aggregate throughput of billions of tokens per day.  After content is embedded, it is dual\u2011indexed into both a vector store and a graph database, so retrieval can combine dense similarity search with graph\u2011based neighborhood expansion under a sub\u2011300\u202fms latency budget. [supermemory](https://supermemory.ai/research)\n\nThe public surface is a versioned HTTPS Memory API (`api.supermemory.ai/v3`) plus an LLM\u2011compatible router endpoint that proxies to providers such as OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, and Groq while injecting retrieved context.  The same underlying API is also exposed via an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server, enabling multi\u2011client access to a shared, user\u2011scoped memory space. [skywork](https://skywork.ai/skypage/en/supermemory-ai-memory-guide/1978325892531089408)\n\n## Memory model and data flow\n\nAt ingestion time, arbitrary inputs (conversation turns, documents, URLs, uploaded files) are normalized, chunked, vectorized, and written as \u201cmemories\u201d with metadata (user id, project id, timestamps, semantic tags).  Each memory is simultaneously added to the vector index and to a graph index where edges encode semantic, temporal, and source relationships, which supports higher\u2011order reasoning such as temporal consistency and multi\u2011hop recall.  Supermemory\u2019s research stack targets benchmarks like LongMemEval, focusing on high\u2011noise, 100k+ token environments and evaluating information extraction, temporal reasoning, preference tracking, and conflict resolution across extended histories. [jimmysong](https://jimmysong.io/ai/supermemory/)\n\nOn recall, the router or API issues a query embedding, performs vector k\u2011NN search, prunes using graph\u2011aware ranking, and returns a compact context bundle conditioned on both the current prompt and long\u2011term user state.  This bundle is serialized into system and context messages that are prepended to the downstream LLM call, effectively giving the model \u201cunlimited\u201d conversational history without violating provider token limits.  The retrieval pipeline is optimized for cost: aggressive chunking, salience scoring, and token\u2011budgeted packing reduce prompt size by up to ~70% while preserving answer quality. [betterstack](https://betterstack.com/community/guides/ai/memory-with-supermemory/)\n\n## Integration surfaces\n\nThere are three primary integration modes: direct Memory API usage, the Memory Router, and MCP.  In the API\u2011centric pattern, applications call CRUD\u2011style endpoints to upsert, query, and scope memories (e.g., per user or project), and then manually wire retrieved context into their prompts.  With the router, existing OpenAI\u2011compatible SDKs can be pointed at a Supermemory proxy URL instead of directly at the provider; the router intercepts the request, performs memory operations, and forwards the transformed payload, requiring essentially no code changes beyond base URL and a couple of headers (`x-supermemory-api-key`, `x-sm-user-id`, optional project scoping).  The MCP server exposes the same capabilities as tools (`memory`, `recall`) to any MCP\u2011compatible client, enabling a unified, persistent memory hub across different frontends and platforms. [supermemory](https://supermemory.ai/docs/supermemory-mcp/introduction)\n\n## Operational and security properties\n\nSupermemory is designed as an enterprise\u2011grade, multi\u2011tenant system with SOC\u202f2\u2011aligned controls, encryption in transit and at rest, and fine\u2011grained access control over memory pools.  It supports deployment in public cloud, hybrid, or fully self\u2011hosted environments, with redundant storage and horizontal scaling of its vector+graph stack to maintain sub\u2011300\u202fms recall under load.  In production use, it underpins agents with cross\u2011session user profiles, RAG over heterogeneous knowledge bases, and shared memory pools across services, effectively acting as the canonical **memory** plane for AI systems rather than a monolithic, model\u2011internal context window. [skywork](https://skywork.ai/skypage/en/Supermemory-AI-The-Ultimate-Guide-to-Your-AI's-Perfect-Memory/1975011238599127040)", "source": "user_input", "metadata": {}, "created_at": "2026-03-01T01:56:02.674881+00:00"}}, "summary": "logged ARTIFACT_INGESTED"}}
